{"type":"message","id":"0d966e5b","parentId":"c1f9bc00","timestamp":"2026-04-25T22:05:34.364Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_j0fxzp2bb3re_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/CozyColonials_CompetitorAnalysis/YOUTUBE_SHORTS_ANALYSIS.md:In three days it has affected seventy percent of the population. Day after day they set sail from New York, Boston and Philadelphia to transport such numbers. The number of transports and routes multiplies. Soon ships dock simultaneously Liverpool, Brest, Bordeaux and even Marseille. During the eight-day crossing, platoons of contact cases become battalions of flu victims. Spain is the first to break the news of the illness and trees neutral and its newspapers are free to inform the world. The illness will henceforth be called the Spanish Flu.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/CozyColonials_CompetitorAnalysis/YOUTUBE_SHORTS_ANALYSIS.md:The Vietnam War holds many hidden facts beyond the well-known conflict. For instance, the Ho Chi Minh Trail, a key supply route for North Vietnamese forces, stretched over 12,000 miles and even extended into Laos and Cambodia. To avoid detection, the US extensively used herbicides like Agent Orange to defoliate jungles, leaving lasting environmental and health impacts still felt today. Tunnel Rats were soldiers specially trained to navigate the vast network of underground tunnels used by the Viet Cong, often facing booby traps and scarce oxygen. Additionally, psychological warfare was employed heavily, with both sides using propaganda and ghost tapes to intimidate the enemy. The war saw extensive use of helicopters, transforming combat tactics and battlefield mobility.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/CozyColonials_CompetitorAnalysis/YOUTUBE_SHORTS_ANALYSIS.md:The Vietnam War holds many hidden facts beyond the well-known conflict. For instance, the Ho Chi Minh Trail, a key supply route for North Vietnamese forces, stretched over 12,000 miles and even extended into Laos and Cambodia. To avoid detection, the US extensively used herbicides like Agent Orange to defoliate jungles, leaving lasting environmental and health impacts still felt today. Tunnel Rats were soldiers specially trained to navigate the vast network of underground tunnels used by the Viet Cong, often facing booby traps and scarce oxygen. Additionally, psychological warfare was employed heavily, with both sides using propaganda and ghost tapes to intimidate the enemy. The war saw extensive use of helicopters, transforming combat tactics and battlefield mobility.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/CozyColonials_CompetitorAnalysis/YOUTUBE_SHORTS_ANALYSIS.md:\"I am leaving Lisbon in 1497 on a mission given to me by King Manuel. We travel near Africa's West Coast and must cross the Cape of Good Hope, which is considered very dangerous. Many ships have already sunk near the Cape of Good Hope. We are also in great danger. In Malindi we found an experienced Arab navigator who will help us cross the Indian Ocean directly to India. We are crossing the Indian Ocean. Many are becoming weak from illness. But now we cannot turn back. We have been at sea for many months. And now it seems we are near India. But still not full certainty. Wait. I see land. If we are right, this might be the place we have been searching for for so long. We have arrived in Calicut, India in 1498. The ruler here is called Zamorin. And there is a very large trade of spices here. Today we have discovered the sea route from Europe to India. And this discovery will go on to completely change trade and history.\"\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/AppIdeas/AppIdea1/.expo/types/router.d.ts:import * as Router from 'expo-router';\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/AppIdeas/AppIdea1/.expo/types/router.d.ts:export * from 'expo-router';\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/AppIdeas/App