{"type":"message","id":"8ea1a886","parentId":"ddeaccd4","timestamp":"2026-04-25T22:16:26.987Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm the file exists. The issue is that server-https.cjs serves `index.html` when the file doesn't exist, and apparently when it DOES exist it's serving Mission Control. Wait, let me look at the routing again:\n\n```javascript\nlet filePath = path.join(distDir, url === '/' ? 'index.html' : url);\nif (!fs.existsSync(filePath) || fs.statSync(filePath).isDirectory()) {\n  filePath = path.join(distDir, 'index.html');\n}\n```\n\nSo if `/route-camera.html` exists, it should serve it. But it's serving Mission Control instead... unless the serve-apps.cjs (port 8787) is still serving it to the 3443 server somehow? No that doesn't make sense.\n \nOh wait—Tailscale DNS resolves `100.103.22.35` to the Mac's local IP. So when Bobby navigates to `https://100.103.22.35:3443/`, he's hitting port 3443 on the Mac where my HTTPS server is running. The server should be serving files directly from the dist directory, but something's off with how the route-camera.html file is being handled.\n\nLet me trace through what's actually happening: when the request comes in for `/route-camera.html`, my code constructs the file path and checks if the file exists. If it does exist and isn't a directory, it should serve that file directly instead of falling back to index.html. But Bobby's seeing Mission Control, which suggests either the file isn't actually there or there's something else going on with how the request is being routed.\n","thinkingSignature":"d66be172df1965753f4b6392a092566cdab7b7681c9622dbb8f3070f23600a5e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3fs6pmd36jnk_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s https://localhost:3443/route-camera.html -k | head -20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":87,"output":370,"cacheRead":41984,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens"